               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18410823-name-1675" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18410823-name-1675" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18410823-name-1675" type="surname" value="ROBINSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18410823-name-1675" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>ROBERT ROBINSON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a carpenter, and live in Magdalen-street, Southwark. The prisoner was my journeyman—he had no tools of his own, and I allowed him to use my tools on my premises, but not to take them away—I missed the planes and other things stated—some of them are here—the rest I cannot find.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PHILLIPS</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Have you been in the habit of pawning things? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I have pawned many things on my own account, but I never suffered a man to do it—I never authorized the prisoner to pawn any thing, that I swear—I paid him 28<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. a week, and found him in tools, which is not usually done—I do not owe him any thing; on the con<lb></lb>trary, he owes me money, and here is proof positive in his own handwrit<lb></lb>ing—I never said, after he bad pawned tools for me, "Don't take any more tools; if you want money, ask me for it, and you shall have it;" nor any thing of the kind.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18410823-name-1676" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18410823-name-1676" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18410823-name-1676" type="surname" value="MATTHEWS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18410823-name-1676" type="given" value="EDWARD"></interp>EDWARD MATTHEWS</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable M</hi> 68.) I took the prisoner 09. the 14th of August—I told him it was for stealing Mr. Robinson's tools—he said he had them, and had made away with them—he gave me the duplicates, and I found these tools at the pawnbroker's—when the pri<lb></lb>soner was in the station he fell on his knees, and begged forgiveness.</p>
